<h3 id="workbench">
<a class="heading-anchor" href="#workbench" hidden><svg width="16" height="16"><use xlink:href="https://thisweek.gnome.org/images/icons.svg#anchor"></use></svg></a>Workbench <a href="https://github.com/sonnyp/Workbench/"><svg width='16' height='16'><use xlink:href='https://thisweek.gnome.org/images/icons.svg#link'></use></svg></a>
</h3><p>A sandbox to learn and prototype with GNOME technologies.</p>
<p><a href="https://matrix.to/#/@sonny:gnome.org">Sonny</a> announces</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Workbench 46 is <a href="https://flathub.org/apps/re.sonny.Workbench">out on Flathub</a>! Here are the highlights</p>
<p>Everybody is excited about them so I&rsquo;ll start by saying you can try libadwaita 1.5 adaptive dialogs with the new &ldquo;Dialog&rdquo; and &ldquo;Message Dialogs&rdquo; demos in the Library.</p>
<p>Workbench now shows inline diagnostics for Rust and Python.</p>
<p>A new Library demo &ldquo;Snapshot&rdquo; was added to demonstrate one of GTK4 coolest feature.</p>
<p>26 additional demos have been ported to Python</p>
<p>5 additional demos have been ported to Vala</p>
<p><a href="https://release.gnome.org/46/developers/index.html#workbench">The GNOME 46 release notes includes all the changes between Workbench 45 and 46.</a></p>
<p>Thank you to all contributors

<img src="https://thisweek.gnome.org/posts/2024/03/twig-140/7b68bbce921f0c4a18a8d108bc1652f37b91c3a21770499732490158080.png" alt="" />


